column4:
It's basically of no benefit to me.  I'm not being compensated, it is going to take up a reasonable amount of my time (at least a few hours), and since I'm 44 years old and grew up with my elderly relatives, I have a pretty good idea of what kind of health risks I'm going to face as I grow older - in fact I'm starting to experience them now - so whatever the analysis reveals is unlikely to be very surprising or helpful. I don't particularly care about how much it benefits mankind or science, so that's out too.\
\
There's also the issue of (slight) risk, my information being made public, discrimination, or the chance I commit some crime and it ends up implicating me.  None of these things would dissuade me if I felt I would receive some benefit from participating, but since I already have decided i won't and don't want to do it, they're just additional reasons not to.
column45: It was well organized and laid out in a logical manner; when I was answering the questions, I could usually anticipate where the information would be found.
column46: It had a lot of gray areas concerning risks I *might* run; my information might be legally or illegally compromised, revealing data to third parties might disclose my identity, law enforcement might get access to my information, insurance companies might discriminate against me. If I weren't already disinclined to participate, the lack of detail about those risks might give me pause.

column4: I would most likely not participate in this study.  It seems to me that the potential risks are greater and are more significant than the possible benefits, especially considering that the benefits are inconclusive, and only can be interpreted in very probabilistic and relative terms.   Good, regular routine preventative health care, paired with healthy, consistent lifestyle choices, behaviors, and postive environmental conditions perhaps offer much more substantive, predictable protection against various afflictions and diseases, even though the genomic data analysis in question would certainly prove worthwhile as an additional interpretative tool in managing one's personal and family health.
column45: The consent form presented contained a great deal of useful information.   However, it could have been organized and topically presented in a more informative, easier to read format.   I would have liked to see the use of a much more structured approach, using more headings, subtopics, and enermerated lists and items.  Also, links could and should be added to provide respondents with additional detail on the current state of various complicated topics and overall, genomic research, (what other national bodies, countries, etc, are engaged in such research, and what has been their experience?) and also on the topic of the potential advantanges and disadvantages of respondent participation.   There remained too many unanswered questions concerning the privacy and security of the genomic data collected that make me uneasy, for example.   I would want to know more about my rights, the current law surrounding this topic, and what concrete precautions will be taken to assure the abolute integ
column46: It is sometimes hard to follow because it is overly general about the section or topic under discussion at any one point.  I often felt like it had been over-edited.  Perhaps an intitial abstract, or executive summary might be best presented first, and then a more structured document offered, with links, should the user care to delve deeper into the subject matter presented.  Also, video content could be developed as a companion piece in complementing the content of the provided consent form.

column4: This was tough.  I had to weigh the pros and the cons of consent carefully.  I think my biggest concern was that there might be an error which would lead me to believe I was either better off or worse off than I really am.  Other concerns were of course someone misusing the information though so unlikely I didn't think it too badly.  Also if I did find out I had something while I could do something about it I didn't like the idea that stress might be added.  Sometimes what you don't know can help you in the short run.  That being said in the long run and in practical health sense it's better to know than not to know so the more information the better.  This is why I ultimately decided that I would choose to do accept if offered this sort of testing.

column45: i did like that the order of information was easy to follow.  it was laid out in a simple and familiar manner.  with the table of contents and each section it was easy to find what i needed to find.  the information was also presented in a manner that would allow for it to be easily read and understood.
column46: the overall amount of reading that was required was kind of long.  some of the information may be difficult for one to understand if they are not familiar with this kind of disclosure.  it was not terribly difficult to comprehend.  it would be nice to have some more detailed information on how the information will be used and how the information will be protected.  those would be the two biggest areas of concern as i would not want to others to benefit from my information.

column4: It would be more interesting, despite the risks, to find out such things as which diseases or conditions I may be susceptible too. And finally, there is always the possibility that future technology will allow the use of DNA to help treat and cure any future conditions I may have.  Well worth it.

 I also would get anxious knowing that I had a higher chance of developing something that may or may not happen.  I understand that preventative medicine is key but sometimes, unfortunately, I'm in denial about health issues I may have.

column4: I think it would be incredibly beneficial for me to know exactly what my genetic makeup happens to be. The information could also be passed on to my children, so they could be aware of what possible diseases they would be prone to in the future.

column4: I would participate because I would want to help further scientific discoveries on the subject. I had some hesitations, particularly when thinking about the information being stored on servers and how someone could breach the servers to gain access to the information. But, honestly, people that do that sort of thing are usually after credit card numbers and such, rather than genomic information. Because of that, I think the threat of leaks is less likely. The other hesitation I would have is learning that I have a higher chance for a disease and that possibly causing me stress. I'd worry a bit about a sort of medical student syndrome psychology, as well, where one would learn about their predisposition to a disease and then they would start "feeling it" even if they don't actually have it. But, with that said, I still think the good of the program outweighs the risks.
